 {"id":"bd-3fb","title":"Implement ctx.read_resource() for cross-component access","description":"# Context: Read Resource from Handler

## Background
Python FastMCP allows reading resources from within tool handlers via ctx.read_resource(). This enables tools to access configured resources without reimplementing logic, promoting code reuse and DRY principles.

## Requirements

### McpContext API
```rust
impl McpContext {
    /// Read a resource from within a handler
    ///
    /// This allows tools to access resources configured on the same server,
    /// enabling composition and code reuse.
    ///
    /// # Example
    /// ```rust
    /// #[tool]
    /// async fn process_config(ctx: &McpContext) -> Result<String, ToolError> {
    ///     // Read the config resource
    ///     let config = ctx.read_resource("config://app").await?;
    ///
    ///     // Process the config content
    ///     let text = config.contents.first()
    ///         .and_then(|c| c.as_text())
    ///         .ok_or(ToolError::InvalidConfig)?;
    ///
    ///     Ok(format!("Config loaded: {}", text))
    /// }
    /// ```
    pub async fn read_resource(&self, uri: &str) -> McpResult<ReadResourceResult>

    /// Read a resource and parse as JSON
    pub async fn read_resource_json<T: DeserializeOwned>(&self, uri: &str) -> McpResult<T>

    /// Read a resource as text
    pub async fn read_resource_text(&self, uri: &str) -> McpResult<String>
}
```

### Implementation Architecture
McpContext needs access to Router to call resource handlers:

```rust
pub struct McpContextInner {
    // ... existing fields ...
    router: Option<Arc<Router>>,  // Access to server's router
    resource_read_depth: u32,     // Prevent infinite recursion
}

const MAX_RESOURCE_READ_DEPTH: u32 = 10;

impl McpContext {
    pub async fn read_resource(&self, uri: &str) -> McpResult<ReadResourceResult> {
        // Check recursion depth
        if self.inner.resource_read_depth >= MAX_RESOURCE_READ_DEPTH {
            return Err(McpError::internal("Maximum resource read depth exceeded"));
        }

        let router = self.inner.router.as_ref()
            .ok_or_else(|| McpError::internal("No router available in context"))?;

        // Create child context with incremented depth
        let child_ctx = self.with_incremented_depth();

        // Find and call resource handler
        router.read_resource(&child_ctx, uri).await
    }

    fn with_incremented_depth(&self) -> McpContext {
        McpContext {
            inner: Arc::new(McpContextInner {
                resource_read_depth: self.inner.resource_read_depth + 1,
                ..(*self.inner).clone()
            })
        }
    }
}
